properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: First taste of wintry weather likely for parts of Nova Scotia Friday night into Saturday. A weather system expected to bring some rain to the province Thursday night and Friday will usher in much colder air later in the day Friday and Saturday. As this colder air arrives from the northwest, showers will turn to periods of snow Friday evening which could give local accumulations especially to the Annapolis Valley, northern Nova Scotia and Cape Breton. Saturday will be a cold and blustery day with onshore flurries and temperatures struggling to climb above zero in many areas. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Wintry conditions possible across the Island later Friday and persisting into Saturday. A weather system is expected to bring some rain to Prince Edward Island later Thursday and into Friday. Much colder air and stronger northwest winds will begin moving in from the north later in the day Friday, changing any remaining showers to periods of snow Friday evening which could give local accumulations. Saturday will be a cold and blustery day with onshore flurries and temperatures struggling to climb above zero in many areas. In addition, there is a possibility of higher than normal water levels as well as large waves impacting coastlines where winds blow onshore. The highest risk is for parts of north to west facing coastlines where strong northwesterly winds will persist Friday night into Saturday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain and snow followed by colder temperatures expected over New Brunswick beginning Thursday night into Friday, with a cold and blustery day in store for Saturday. A weather system will develop on Thursday and bring rain to southern New Brunswick beginning Thursday afternoon with snow expected over northern regions, with the rain/snow boundary likely across central New Brunswick. Rainfall amounts of 15 to 30 millimetres are possible over southern sections with 10 centimetres or more of snow possible for the northern half of the province Thursday night. As colder air moves into the province from the north on Friday, flurries or periods of snow could give additional accumulations in some areas, and temperatures will struggle to reach the freezing mark in many areas. These cold temperatures will persist into Saturday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain or wet snow for the Islands Thursday night, followed by colder temperatures, flurries and strong winds for Friday and Saturday. A weather system will bring rain or wet snow to the Islands beginning late in the day Thursday, then change to flurries on Friday as colder air and stronger winds move into the region from the northwest. Saturday will be an unseasonably cold and blustery day with frequent flurries that could give a few centimetres accumulation. The storm will cause higher than normal water levels as well as large waves and rough and pounding surf, mainly along coastlines where winds blow onshore. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
